ranian society, particularly the time during and after the controversial 2009 presidential election, a watershed moment in the postrevolutionary history of Iran. While regional specialists may find studies on specific themes useful, the aim of this volume is to provide broad narratives of actor-based conceptions of media technology, an approach that focuses on the experiential and social networking processes of digital practices in the information era extended beyond cultural specificities. Students and scholars of regional and media studies will find this volume rich with empirical and theoretical insights on the subject of how technologies shape political and everyday life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aSocial media - Iran. 0aSocial mediaxPolitical aspectszIran. 0aSocial mediazIran. 4aArea Studies : Middle East Studies. 4aCommunication : Political Communication. 4aPolitics and Law : Democratization. 4aScience, Mathematics, and Technology : Internet. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh1 aAkhavan, Niki, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElahifar, Kobra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEloranta, Jari, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEsfahlani, Mohammad Sadeghi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFalasiri, Arash, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFaris, David M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFaris, David M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGhanavizi, Nazanin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGheytanchi, Elham, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKermani, Hossein, econtributor.4ctb4https:/